        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 3. 1878</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have many apologies to make, for I have just found the missing number of Kosmos. I dispatch by this mornings post the December number. I will before long read the discussion on stridulation to which you refer.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>As my son Francis does not attend at all to entomology but devotes all his time to plant physiology, it would be hardly worth his while to belong to yr society—which has my best wishes for its success.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11305.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Raphael Meldola, 1 January [1878]</ref>. CD had asked Meldola to return the October 1877 issue of <hi rend="italic">Kosmos</hi>, and offered to send him the December 1877 issue. In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11308.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter to CD of 2 January [1878]</ref>, Meldola had recommended a discussion of stridulation in the <hi rend="italic">Transactions of the Entomological Society of London</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Meldola had invited <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> to become a member of the Entomological Society of London (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11308.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Raphael Meldola, 2 January [1878]</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
